INGREDIENT SPOTLIGHT SERIES PART 3 ||COLLAGEN||

Collagen is all the rage these days, with every other product containing it. So is it worth the hype? 
Let’s first talk about what it does. 
🤍Collagen forms an essential part of the supportive framework of your skin. It’s what gives your skin its strength. It works in conjunction with other ingredients like roasting, providing your skin with elasticity. As you age, the collagen production decreases and your skin starts to sag and wrinkle
🤍Retains moisture
🤍Improves skin tone and skin texture
🤍Boosts fibroblast production in the dermal layer of your skin, thereby enhancing cell production and helping with wound healing and tissue repair 

Coming to the big question- do they actually work? Collagen preparations are largely available in two forms:
🩷Topical preparations- honestly, these only serve to provide a little extra hydration because the particle size is too large to enter the skin and boost collagen production. There is no evidence to prove its effectiveness. 
🩷Collagen supplements: when taken in the form of hydrolysed collagen, there have been studies that show an improvement in skin elasticity and wrinkles. The issue with these studies is two fold- they were largely funded by the companies manufacturing collagen supplements and these studies were mainly conducted on older women with nutrient deficiencies. 

What’s your take on collagen in skincare?

Here are three skincare mistakes I made so that you don’t make them too!
1. Using whichever product is going viral without researching the ingredients: Guys I promise you, there’s no magical product that will fix all your skin problems in a week. Most of the times, influencers are given a script to follow. Do your research before buying a product to make sure the ingredients will suit your skin. Don’t just buy a product because it’s viral. 

2. Using too many actives in the same routine: I’m super impatient and I hate waiting haha. I want all my skin problems to go away asap. This leads to me mixing all the actives that can potentially fix my skin in one routine. Don’t be like me. You’re just gonna end up damaging your skin barrier. Remember- less is more. 

3. Not listening to my skin: there are days your skin does better with the simplest routine possible. If your skin is looking angry and irritated, listen to it. Don’t use that retinol or that exfoliant. Give your skin some rest. 

Do you make these mistakes too? Let me know in the poll!

I love a good face mask as much as the next person. But for me, the VT cosmetics Cica daily soothing mask just wasn’t it. Here’s why:
😢It comes in a box of 30 masks which you have to use over two months. I feel like given the fact using masks daily is known to be harmful for your skin, it should have a longer shelf life,
😢It’s super expensive and for the price point, you would expect something magical. But all it does is that it soothes your skin and hydrates it a teeny tiny bit. Not worth the price at all imo
😢Honestly it generates A LOT of waste. Given the current global situation, I feel like the amount of waste this generates is unwarranted
😢It takes so long! You’re supposed to keep it on for 15 minutes. I feel like the ordinary barrier support serum does the exact same thing in literally ten seconds. 

But I want to know your thoughts! Is this something you would try? Let me know in the poll!

I don’t intend to for this post to be seen as me bashing a brand. I would rather the brand see this post and change their marketing strategies. But I have to speak out about it. 

I think marketing a product as skin whitening in 2025 just shows that the marketing team is lazy and lacks creativity. There are so many terms that can be used like ‘lightens hyperpigmentation’ or ‘helps with dark spots’. Why are we still stuck on skin lightening? 

That said, this brand is relatively small. Does that mean we should let it go? Vote in the poll and let me know what your thoughts are in the comments!
